						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">RetroArch is an emulator framework that you get emulator plugins for. It handles the main interface, menus, the final screen compositing step (upscaling filters, including NTSC simulation), etc. so that all the emulators have the same front-end feel and you can switch between them easily. So the suggestion was that you could make a game as a DLL plugin for this.</div><br />While probably a good idea this souds extremely complicated. I've already sucessed (I think) at compiling .so files on linux, but I never managed to get .dll on Windows working fine with gcc.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">It's a little bit &quot;NIH,&quot; but personally I'd write my own (software) rendering code in C or C++ and expose an interface to the Python code.</div><br />Sounds like a decent option, too.</div>

